{
    "analysis": "Previously we loaded metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv and error_logs.csv and aggregated them by (cmdb_id, KPI/trace/log name). The aggregation produced metric_stats, trace_stats and log_stats and a combined_top table (top-20 by sample count). The combined_top is dominated by metric groups (31 samples per series) including IG01, Redis01, Tomcat02, Tomcat04 etc. Global thresholds (p95) for each series were computed and stored in those kernel variables. No time-window filtering or anomaly detection has been done yet, so we do not yet know which components/KPIs breached thresholds during the incident window (2021-03-04 02:30 to 03:00 UTC+8).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the already computed metric_stats, trace_stats, and log_stats (these contain per-(cmdb_id,name) global p95 values), filter the raw metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv rows to the incident time window: 2021-03-04 02:30:00 through 2021-03-04 03:00:00 in timezone UTC+8. Save these filtered tables in kernel variables named metric_window, trace_window, log_window, and error_logs_window. Then, for each (source in [metric, trace, log]) aggregated group (cmdb_id + name) compute: count_in_window, anomaly_count where anomaly is value >= global_p95 for that group, earliest_anomaly_timestamp (minimum timestamp among anomalies), and max_value_in_window. Join p95 from the precomputed stats. Return a compact table (limit to top 20 rows) with columns: source, cmdb_id, name, count_in_window, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, p95. Sort by anomaly_count descending then earliest_anomaly_timestamp ascending. Also return the number of rows in each filtered table (metric_window, trace_window, log_window, error_logs_window). Do not print full raw series; only return the compact aggregated table and the four filtered-row-counts."
}

{
    "analysis": "The previous step loaded global p95 thresholds for each (cmdb_id, KPI) group and filtered the raw telemetry into the incident window (2021-03-04 02:30 to 03:00 UTC+8). The compact aggregated table shows many metric groups (across IG01/IG02/MG01/MG02/Mysql*/Redis*/Tomcat*) had every sample in-window equal-or-above their global P95 (count_in_window=31, anomaly_count=31) and earliest anomaly at 02:30+08:00. error_logs had 0 rows in-window. However, many of those anomalies are exactly equal to the p95 (value == p95) which may be a side-effect of p95 being equal to the max or a constant metric; these should not be treated as severe breaches necessarily. We need to distinguish true breaches (value > p95) from equals, and rank groups/components by breach severity to localize the most significant faults. At this point we have not yet identified a single faulty component or the exact root-cause time beyond the window start, so the investigation is not complete.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the already-filtered incident-window tables and the precomputed per-(cmdb_id,name) p95 values, compute per metric-group (only metric groups): count_in_window, count_gt_p95 (number of samples with value > p95), count_eq_p95 (number of samples with value == p95), max_value_in_window, p95, relative_breach = (max_value_in_window - p95) / p95. Handle p95==0 by setting relative_breach = NaN or a large sentinel when max_value_in_window>0 (report such cases explicitly). Return two compact outputs: (A) top 20 metric groups sorted by relative_breach descending (columns: cmdb_id, name, count_in_window, count_gt_p95, count_eq_p95, max_value_in_window, p95, relative_breach, earliest_timestamp_of_value_gt_p95 if any else null); (B) aggregated by component (cmdb_id): number_of_metric_groups_with_count_gt_p95>0, max_relative_breach_among_groups, earliest_timestamp_of_any_gt_p95. Limit rows to top 20 for (A) and top 20 for (B). Also return the total number of metric groups that had any sample with value > p95. Do not output raw series rows."}

{
    "analysis": "We have completed preprocessing and metric-level anomaly detection for the incident window (2021-03-04 02:30–03:00 UTC+8). The metric analysis shows widespread breaches across many components: numerous metric groups per component exceeded their global P95 during the window. Many groups have p95 == 0 causing infinite relative breach scores — these must be interpreted carefully (likely sparse/rare metrics that became non-zero). The highest-impact components by count of breached metric groups are Mysql02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Mysql01, Tomcat01, IG02, apache01, Redis01, etc. Earliest observed metric anomalies are at 2021-03-04 02:30:00+08. At this stage we cannot pick a single root cause component because multiple components show faults at the same time and we must use traces to identify downstream faulty service(s) and logs to determine the reason. Next, we should analyze trace-level anomalies in the same incident window to find which services show latency or error propagation and to help pick the most downstream faulty service(s).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Analyze trace events in the incident window to localize downstream faulty services. Using the precomputed trace_stats (which contains global p95 per (cmdb_id,trace_name)) and the filtered incident-window trace table (trace_window), compute for each trace group (cmdb_id + trace_name): count_in_window, count_gt_p95 (value > p95), count_eq_p95 (value == p95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp (min timestamp where value > p95), max_value_in_window, p95, and relative_breach = (max_value_in_window - p95)/p95 (handle p95==0 by setting relative_breach to inf when max_value_in_window>0). Limit output to top 20 trace groups sorted by count_gt_p95 desc, then relative_breach desc. Also return: (A) number of distinct trace groups with any sample > p95; (B) list of unique cmdb_id values among those trace groups (limit to top 20). Additionally, restrict a second, compact view to only the previously top metric-impacted components (Mysql02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Mysql01, Tomcat01, IG02, apache01, Redis01) and show the same aggregated trace metrics for those components (limit top 20). Return only these aggregated tables and the two counts/lists; do not print raw time series." }

{
    "analysis": "We completed preprocessing, global-threshold calculation (P95) and incident-window filtering. Metric analysis found pervasive P95 breaches across many components at the start of the window (02:30+08), with Mysql02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Mysql01, Tomcat01, IG02, IG01, MG01/MG02 among the top impacted components. Notably, several Mysql02 metric groups show large relative breaches (e.g., Innodb pending writes/fsyncs and related counters with relative_breach ≈ 19) and earliest anomalies at 2021-03-04 02:30:00+08. Trace analysis shows downstream latency increases (MG01/MG02, IG01/IG02, Tomcat04/Tomcat01) with earliest trace anomalies ~02:33–02:36+08, suggesting service-level slowdowns emerged shortly after the Mysql02 metric deviations. Error logs in-window appeared to be zero globally in an earlier check, but log features (log.csv) have not yet been examined in detail for the candidate components. We have not yet confirmed a single root cause component/time/reason: metrics point strongly at Mysql02 (earliest, high-severity metric breaches), while traces indicate latency propagation downstream starting a few minutes later. Additional log-level evidence is needed to confirm root cause and exact occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the candidate components [Mysql02, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Mysql01, Tomcat01, IG02, IG01, MG01, MG02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04] use the already-filtered incident-window log table (log_window) and error_logs_window. 1) Aggregate log_window by (cmdb_id, log_name) and compute: count_in_window, sum_value, max_value, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp. Return the top 20 rows sorted by sum_value descending with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, count_in_window, sum_value, max_value, earliest_timestamp, latest_timestamp. 2) From error_logs_window, return up to 20 rows (timestamp, cmdb_id, message) filtered to these same candidate components (sorted by timestamp ascending). Keep outputs compact and do not return raw metric/trace series." }

